    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Industry Guide</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-6">
        Packaging Line Conveyor Systems
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl space-y-4">
        <p>
          Packaging line conveyors connect every machine in a packaging operation -- from fillers and sealers through case packers and palletizers to stretch wrappers and shipping docks. These conveyors handle product transport, accumulation between machines running at different speeds, lane changes for multipack configurations, and elevation changes between mezzanines and floor-level equipment.
        </p>
        <p>
          A well-designed packaging line conveyor system maximizes overall equipment effectiveness (OEE) by preventing any single machine stoppage from shutting down the entire line.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article>
  <!-- Primary / Secondary / Tertiary Packaging Flow -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="flow-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Packaging Flow</div>
      <h2 id="flow-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Primary, Secondary &#x26; Tertiary Packaging Conveyors
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Packaging operations divide into three stages, each with different conveyor requirements for product handling, speed, load capacity, and accumulation.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Primary Packaging Conveyors</h3>
        <p>
          Primary packaging conveyors handle individual products during filling, sealing, capping, and labeling. These conveyors require precise positioning, gentle handling, and consistent spacing. Belt conveyors dominate primary packaging because they provide a continuous, stable surface for bottles, pouches, cartons, and trays.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="/conveyor-functions/indexing-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Indexing conveyors</a> position products at exact stop points for fill heads, cappers, labelers, and vision inspection cameras. Servo-driven indexing provides repeatable positioning accuracy within fractions of an inch. <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/beverage/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Tabletop chain conveyors</a> carry round containers (bottles, cans, jars) between filler, capper, and labeler stations because the flat chain surface prevents tipping.
        </p>
        <p>
          Primary packaging conveyors in food plants require <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food-grade construction</a> with FDA-compliant belt materials and stainless steel frames. Product-contact conveyors in pharmaceutical lines need GMP-compliant designs.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Secondary Packaging Conveyors</h3>
        <p>
          Secondary packaging conveyors transport cases, cartons, bundles, trays, and shrink-wrapped multipacks. Products at this stage are sealed, so food-contact requirements typically do not apply (though some food safety audit schemes require washdown capability even in secondary packaging zones).
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Roller conveyors</a> (gravity, powered, and <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR</a>) handle the majority of secondary packaging transport. Cases and cartons have flat, rigid bottoms that ride well on rollers. <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Accumulation conveyors</a> buffer product between case packers, case sealers, and print-and-apply labelers.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="/conveyor-functions/collating-laning/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Laning and collating conveyors</a> divide single-file product streams into multiple lanes for case packing. <a href="/conveyor-functions/reject-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Reject conveyors</a> divert out-of-spec product, failed checkweigher results, or metal detector rejects off the main line.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Tertiary Packaging Conveyors</h3>
        <p>
          Tertiary packaging conveyors handle palletized loads from palletizer discharge through stretch wrapping to staging and shipping docks. <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Pallet conveyors</a> carry the heaviest loads in the packaging line -- standard loads range from 1,000 to 4,000 lbs. <a href="/conveyor-types/cdlr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Chain-driven live roller (CDLR) conveyors</a> are the standard pallet conveyor type.
        </p>
        <p>
          Tertiary conveyors integrate with palletizer outfeed, stretch wrapper infeed/outfeed, pallet labelers, and dock-level staging areas. <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Transfer conveyors</a> (turntables, right-angle transfers, and chain transfers) route pallets between lanes, storage rows, and dock doors.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Packaging Line Layout -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="layout-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Line Layout</div>
      <h2 id="layout-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Packaging Line Layout and Integration Points
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Packaging line conveyor layout determines floor space utilization, operator access, maintenance access, and overall line efficiency. The conveyor system must connect every machine while allowing room for operators, fork trucks, and maintenance crews. Three layout patterns cover most packaging line configurations.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Straight-Line Layout</h3>
        <p>
          Machines and conveyors arrange in a single line from filler to palletizer. This layout minimizes transfers and direction changes. It requires the most floor length but provides the simplest conveyor design. Straight-line layouts work well for single-product lines with limited SKU changeovers.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">U-Shape Layout</h3>
        <p>
          The line starts and ends on the same side of the building, creating a U-shape. Raw material receiving and finished goods shipping share a common building wall. U-shape layouts reduce fork truck travel distance and allow operators to monitor both the upstream and downstream ends of the line. Conveyors require 180-degree direction changes, typically using <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfer conveyors</a> or curved belt sections.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">L-Shape Layout</h3>
        <p>
          The line turns 90 degrees partway through the process. L-shape layouts fit building footprints where a straight line does not fit. They require right-angle transfer conveyors at the turn points. L-shapes work well when primary packaging runs along one wall and secondary/tertiary packaging runs along an adjacent wall.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Key Integration Points</h3>
        <p>
          The most critical conveyor design decisions occur at integration points -- where conveyors connect to machines or change direction. Each integration point requires specific conveyor types, speed matching, and controls coordination.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-4 px-4 mt-8">
        <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[700px]">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Integration Point</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Conveyor Type</th>
              <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Key Requirement</th>
