              <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">50-150 FPM</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Case packer to sealer</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4">Powered roller / MDR</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4">Tracking, orientation</td>
              <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">50-200 FPM</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Sealer to palletizer</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4">Roller + laning</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4">Pattern formation</td>
              <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">50-200 FPM</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Palletizer to stretch wrap</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4"><a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/pallet/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover">Pallet conveyor</a> / CDLR</td>
              <td class="py-4 pr-4">Heavy load, low speed</td>
              <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">20-60 FPM</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Accumulation -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="accumulation-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Accumulation</div>
      <h2 id="accumulation-heading" class="font-display text-4xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Accumulation Sizing for Packaging Lines
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Accumulation conveyors</a> are the most critical component in packaging line design. Every machine on the line stops periodically for jam clearing, changeovers, roll changes, and minor faults. Accumulation buffers absorb these stops so upstream and downstream equipment keeps running.
        </p>
        <p>
          Without adequate accumulation, a single 30-second jam at the case sealer stops the filler, the labeler, and the palletizer. With 3 minutes of accumulation on each side of the case sealer, the rest of the line runs uninterrupted through a 30-second jam clearance.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">How to Calculate Accumulation Length</h3>
        <p>
          The formula for accumulation length:
        </p>
        <p class="font-mono text-ink bg-surface-dim px-4 py-3 border border-border">
          <strong>Accumulation Length (ft) = Buffer Time (min) x Products/min x Product Pitch (ft)</strong>
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Product pitch = product length + gap between products. Buffer time is the number of minutes of production you want to absorb before the upstream machine must stop.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Buffer Time Guidelines</h3>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-4 px-4 mt-4">
          <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse min-w-[600px]">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b-2 border-ink">
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Location</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Minimum Buffer</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Recommended</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Between filler and capper</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">1-2 min</td>
                <td class="py-4">3 min</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Between primary and case packer</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">3 min</td>
                <td class="py-4">5 min</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Between case packer and palletizer</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">3 min</td>
                <td class="py-4">5 min</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Before stretch wrapper</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">2-3 pallet positions</td>
                <td class="py-4">4-5 pallet positions</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">These are starting guidelines. Actual buffer requirements depend on machine reliability data, changeover frequency, and acceptable OEE targets. High-speed lines (200+ products/min) often need 5-10 minutes of buffer.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mt-8 mb-4">Accumulation Conveyor Types</h3>
        <p>
          Three accumulation methods serve different product types:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Zero-pressure (ZPA):</strong> Products stop and queue without touching each other. Uses <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a> with zone sensors. Best for fragile products and printed cartons. Highest cost.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Minimum-pressure:</strong> Products contact each other lightly when stopped. Uses pneumatic or mechanically actuated roller zones. Lower cost than ZPA. Acceptable for rigid cases and cartons.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-ink">Back-pressure (contact):</strong> Products push against each other when stopped. Uses gravity roller or powered roller with a stop. Lowest cost. Only suitable for heavy, rigid products that tolerate contact (steel drums, heavy cases).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Conveyor Types for Packaging Lines -->
  <section class="py-24 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Conveyor Selection</div>
